"1166","1174":"1174","1170":"1170","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cave","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in East Yorkshire called Cave, apparently from a river name derived from Old English <i>cāf</i> ‘swift’.","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Norman and Picard Old French <i>cauf</i> (from Latin <i>calvus</i>) ‘bald’.","French: topographic name for someone who lived in or near a cave, from Old French <i>cave</i> ‘cave’, ‘cellar’ (from Latin <i>cavea</i>, a derivative of <i>cavus</i> ‘hollow’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cavin","meanings":["Scottish (Wigtownshire): variant of <b>Caveen</b>, a shortened form of Manx <i>Mac Dhaimhín</i>, son of <i>Daimhín</i>. The personal name is a diminutive of Gaelic <i>damh</i> ‘bard, poet’.","French: diminutive of   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Caves","meanings":["English: variant of   Cave  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Keeve","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Cave  . This surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chaffee","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): descriptive nickname from a derivative of Old French <i>chauf</i> ‘bald’ (from Latin <i>calvus</i>). Compare   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Cavett","meanings":["Scottish (of French origin): altered form of French <b>Cavet</b>, which is either a diminutive of   Cave   3 or a metonymic occupational name for a laborer, one who used a <i>cavet</i>, an Old Occitan word for a tool for clearing ground for cultivation."]}]},{"name":"Geoffrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic (Frankish and Lombard) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It was in regular use among the counts of Anjou, ancestors of the English royal house of Plantagenet, who were descended from Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou (  1113–51 ). It was a particularly popular name in England and France in the later Middle Ages; notable bearers in England include the poet  Geoffrey Chaucer  (  <i>c.</i>1340–1400 ) and in Wales the chronicler  Geoffrey  of Monmouth (  d. 1155 ). The original form and meaning of the name is disputed. According to one theory, it is merely a variant of   Godfrey ;  others derive the first part from the Germanic word <i>gawia</i> ‘territory’, <i>walah</i> ‘stranger’, or <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. Medieval forms can be found to support all these theories, and it is possible that several names have fallen together, or that the name was subjected to reanalysis by folk etymology at an early date."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":25,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":34,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":69,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Geoffrey de Cave was born about 1190, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Thomas de Cave, was 54 and his mother, Joyce Saint Quintin, was 47. He had at least 1 son. He died in England."},"et":{"about 1190–":"umbes 1190–Surnud","1166–Male":"1166–Surnud","1168–Female":"1168–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1174–Male":"1174–Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1137–Male":"1137–Surnud","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1137":"1137","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1224":"1224","1168":"1168","1145":"1145","1166":"1166","1174":"1174","1170":"1170","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1190–":"noin 1190–Kuollut","1166–Male":"1166–Kuollut","1168–Female":"1168–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1174–Male":"1174–Kuollut","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1215–Male":"1215–Kuollut","1137–Male":"1137–Kuollut","1145–Female":"1145–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1137":"1137","about 1190":"noin 1190","1224":"1224","1168":"1168","1145":"1145","1166":"1166","1174":"1174","1170":"1170","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"about 1190–":"environ 1190–Décédé","1166–Male":"1166–Décédé","1168–Female":"1168–Décédée","1170–Male":"1170–Décédé","1170–Female":"1170–Décédée